{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a352dd8a-939d-4c5e-bfcc-c3dbe0d15968","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nHere's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all your installed workloads, matching them to your current SDK. This is what you need after a SDK update, since your existing workload versions likely don't align with the new SDK.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-downloads and reinstalls workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but doesn't upgrade anything.\n\nSince your issue is a version mismatch caused by the SDK update, `update` is the correct choice:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` workload is present and up to date.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2718c21b-7096-4a98-a789-7b3ce13f30cf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads for the current SDK band. This is what you want after a SDK update, because the workloads need to match the new SDK version.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted or incomplete installations. It doesn't change versions; it just re-downloads and reinstalls the same versions.\n\n\nSo after a .NET SDK update breaks your build, `dotnet workload update` is the command to run — it'll sync your workloads to the new SDK version.","outputTokens":379,"requestId":"D455:16D25D:1BF1DA5:1F81B65:6A07C0FD"},"id":"c8b4af21-9698-4b83-b3d7-3328844d5073","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:57:42.698Z","parentId":"344ed90c-ee79-450